
[1]celebrity

   CELEBRITY, n.

   1. Fame; renown; the distinction or honor publicly bestowed on a nation
   or person, on character or exploits; the distinction bestowed on
   whatever is great or remarkable, and manifested by praises or eulogies;
   as the celebrity of the duke of Wellington; the celebrity of Homer, or
   of the Iliad.

   England acquired celebrity from the triumphs of Marlborough.

   2. Public and splendid transaction; as the celebrity of a marriage. In
   this sense, as used by Bacon, we now use celebration.
